<br>
The key to an enforceable &quot;roleplay&quot; ruleset would be unambiguous rules. They couldn't be a bunch of subjective judgements (those only work in small groups where you can reach a group consensus).<br>
<br>
So, you couldn't have &quot;Rule #18: Pick a racially-appropriate name that reflects your cultural heritage.&quot; - because that is subjective. Maybe I think &quot;Ellywig&quot; sounds very gnomish, but you think all gnomish names have 18 syllables and sound like bad german?<br>
<br>
You would either have to have &quot;Rule #18: Pick a name from one of the appropriate racial lists below:&quot; or something akin to Verant's naming policy and name filter, where you ban specific, defined types of names. &quot;Rule #18c: No numerals used to replace letters in names.&quot; Or, for something like the name rules, you would have to have to have each name submitted to someone for approval - not a very efficient process for a massive EQish game, very doable with small groups (think NWN or tabletop games).<br>
<br>
Once you had that clear ruleset in, you would have a bunch of people testing it initially, and periodic incursions afterwards to see if you still mean it. But the rest of the population would settle in within the limits, just like they do in any other gaming environment. They would match their playstyle and expectations to what was available.<br>
<br>
If you went with anything subjective, you'd have constant bickering that would destroy the server. Period.<br>
<br>
You would have to take an enormous number of game issues and draw lines - where is the line between attacking guards as roleplay and lazy powerlevelling d00dism? Is it roleplay or griefing when someone buffs the monster you are fighting? And so on.<br>
<br>
Ideally, The rules would be set up to encourage a roleplay environment (within whatever game mechanic limits there are). For example, on a &quot;roleplay&quot; server, I would expect the NPCs to speak their native language (and maybe a couple extra) - rather than them being fluent in everything like they are now. Languages start to have value if the game engine gives them value.<br>
<br>
The most fundamental thing you would need to set up a roleplay server is a very cynical outlook regarding your players... you would have to realize that ANY and EVERY loophole that can be used to evade the rules or grief other players will be, and adjust your rules accordingly. You cannot base a ruleset on the assumption that everyone will play fair and do their best to adhere to the spirit of the rules... they don't. Most do, but it only takes that small, dedicated core of wankers to ruin a game - and those folks will be rules lawyers. They will know every nuance, and find a way to argue that they are entitled to their &quot;fun&quot;, regardless of the cost to others.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Ellywig</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
